# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acc-twenty20-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2007-acc-twenty20-cup] The **2007 ACC Twenty20 Cup** was played from 27 October until 2 November 2007 in Kuwait.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2007-acc-twenty20-cup] The ten competing teams were: Afghanistan, Hong Kong, Kuwait, Malaysia, Nepal, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Singapore and the UAE.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2007-acc-twenty20-cup] Group A saw eventual finalists Oman and Afghanistan finish in the top two and qualify for the semi-final stage.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2007-acc-twenty20-cup] Malaysia failed to win a match, despite featuring Somerset player Arul Suppiah in their squad.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2007-acc-twenty20-cup] Group B was a closer group than Group A.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2007-acc-twenty20-cup] The UAE topped the group after winning all four of their games, and hosts Kuwait joined them in the semi-finals after finishing ahead of Singapore.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2009-acc-twenty20-cup] The **2009 ACC Twenty20 Cup** was played between 22 and 30 November 2009 in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2009-acc-twenty20-cup] The twelve competing teams were: Afghanistan, Bahrain, China, Hong Kong, Kuwait, Malaysia, Nepal, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Singapore and the UAE.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2009-acc-twenty20-cup] Afghanistan defeated the United Arab Emirates in the final to win the tournament for the second time, following their joint victory with Oman in 2007.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2009-acc-twenty20-cup] In the third place playoff Oman defeated Kuwait, meaning they will join Afghanistan and the United Arab Emirates for the cricket tournament at the 2010 Asian Games, along with the national teams of Bangladesh, China, India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] It was the second time China hosted the Asian Games, with the first one being Asian Games 1990 in Beijing.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Guangzhou's three neighboring cities, Dongguan, Foshan and Shanwei co-hosted the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Premier Wen Jiabao opened the Games along the Pearl River in Haixinsha Island.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A total of 53 venues were used to host the events.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The design concept of the official logo of the 2010 Asian Games was based on the legend of the Guangzhou's Five Goats, representing the Five Goats as the Asian Games Torch.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A total of 9,704 athletes from 45 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) competed in 476 events of 42 sports and disciplines (28 Olympic sports and 14 non-Olympic sports), making it the largest event in the history of the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Due to reductions in the number of sports for competition in the 2014 Asian Games, these Games marked the final time that six non-Olympic events would be held during the Asian Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] China led the final medal tally, followed by South Korea in second place, and Japan in third place.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] China set a new Games record with 199 gold medals.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] China became the first nation in the history of Asian Games to cross the 400 medal-mark in one edition.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Three world and 103 Asian records were broken.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Macau and Bangladesh won their first ever Asian Games gold medals.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In addition, the badminton men's singles gold medalist Lin Dan was voted as the most valuable player (MVP).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Seoul and Amman dropped out before their bids were officially selected by the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA), leaving only two candidate cities—Guangzhou and Kuala Lumpur—by March 31, 2004.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Seoul withdrew after considering that South Korea hosted the 2002 Games in Busan only eight years earlier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The evaluation committee of the OCA inspected Kuala Lumpur from April 12 to 14 and Guangzhou from April 14 to 16, 2004.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] On April 15, 2004, the Government of Malaysia declared that it would not support the Olympic Council of Malaysia with a Kuala Lumpur bid due to the high cost of hosting the Games, estimated at US$366 million, forcing Kuala Lumpur to withdraw its bid and leaving Guangzhou as the sole bidder.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The OCA unanimously selected Guangzhou to host the 2010 Games during their 23rd General Assembly session in Doha, Qatar, site of the 2006 Asian Games, on July 1, 2004.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] On March 11, 2005, Lin Shusen, then party secretary of the Guangzhou Municipal Committee of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) said the Games "will not cost more than ¥2 billion", in stark contrast to an earlier report, which had claimed that the cost could exceed ¥200 billion.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In March 2009, the director of the marketing department of the Games, Fang Da'er, claimed that the Games were short of funds, due to the lack of sponsorship and the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] An informal estimate put the Games' expenditure at about US$420 million and revenue at US$450 million.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The full spending details would be released before 2013, according to the city's finance chief Zhang Jieming.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] It was later reported that Guangzhou accumulated US$32 billion (¥210 billion) in debt after staging the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The volunteer recruitment program for the 2010 Asian Games began at 9 pm on April 21, 2009, with a target of 60,000 games-time volunteers.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The volunteers were given a green short-sleeve t-shirt, a green long-sleeve t-shirt, a sport jacket, a pair of trousers, a hat, a water bottle, a pair of sport shoes and a waist bag.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Two torch designs were shortlisted in September 2009 for the 2010 Asian Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The organizers chose a design named "The Tide" over one named "Exploit" as the torch of the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] "The Tide" weighed 98 g and was 70 cm long.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] It was tall and straight in shape, while dynamic in terms of image.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The torch relay route was unveiled on March 4, 2010, and due to budgetary issues and the problems related to 2008 Summer Olympics torch relay, the organizers decided to carry it out on a smaller scale than those carried out previously.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The torch was lit at the Great Wall of China on October 9, 2010, and traveled around the Temple of Heaven in Beijing.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] As originally scheduled, 21 cities were present on the relay route, with 2,010 torchbearers expected to carry it from October 12 to November 12, 2010.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Two more cities — Changchun in Jilin and Haiyang in Shandong, the host cities of 2007 Asian Winter Games and 2012 Asian Beach Games respectively, were also later added to the route for a single day on October 15, 2010, increasing the number of torchbearers to 2,068 people.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The official emblem of the Games was unveiled at Sun Yat-sen Memorial Hall on November 26, 2006, to prepare the city to succeed Doha 2006 as Asian Games host city.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] It was a stylized representation of Guangzhou's "Statue of the Five Goats" (Chinese: 五羊雕像; pinyin: *Wǔ yáng diāoxiàng*; Jyutping: *ng5 joeng4 diu1 zoeng6*) fused with a running track.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In Chinese tradition, the goat is a blessing and brings people luck, and the host city Guangzhou is known as the "City of Goats".
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The orange and yellow emblem also resembles a flame.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The mascots of the Games were five goat rams.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] They were unveiled on April 28, 2008, at the Guangzhou Baiyun International Convention and Exhibition Center.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The five goat rams, four small and one large, were named A Xiang (阿祥), A He (阿和), A Ru (阿如), A Yi (阿意) and Le Yangyang (乐羊羊).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The Chinese character "yang" (羊), "ram" or "goat" is an auspicious symbol and Guangzhou is known as "City of Rams".
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A Xiang is characterized as a "handsome, stylish, sincere and brave" goat.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A Xiang wears a blue outfit that resembles the blue ring of the Olympic emblem.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The designers stated that this design symbolizes the ever-running Pearl River and the gentle and kind character and broad and welcoming heart of the people of Guangzhou.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A He is described as an earthy, modest, serene and decisive goat.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A He wears a black outfit that resembles the black ring of the Olympic emblem and symbolizes the grand heritage and long history of the Lingnan culture.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A Ru is described as a beautiful, fashionable, smart and passionate goat.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A Ru wears a red outfit that resembles the red ring of the Olympic emblem and symbolizes the red kapok (*Bombax ceiba*)—the city flower of Guangzhou, which gives Guangzhou its nickname of The City of Flowers.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A Yi is described as a nifty, cute, lively and outgoing goat.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A Yi wears a green outfit that resembles the green ring of the Olympic emblem and symbolizes the city's famous Baiyun Mountain.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Le Yangyang is described as the tall, handsome, sunny and confident leader of the goat ram mascot team.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Le Yangyang wears a yellow outfit that resembles the yellow ring of the Olympic emblem and symbolizes the color of rice grains, as Guangzhou has the nickname, The City of Rice Grains.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The medal designs were unveiled at Guangzhou No.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] 2 Children's Palace on September 29, 2010.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The theme of the design was the "Maritime Silk Road." They featured the Emblem of the Olympic Council of Asia and Guangzhou's kapok flower on the obverse and the Maritime Silk Road image and the games' logo on the reverse.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The Maritime Silk Road image depicts a Chinese boat sailing on the sea, representing Guangzhou as the starting place of Maritime Silk Road, as the most important commercial center and entrepot of the Southern China, Hong Kong and Macau regions.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The official motto of the 2010 Asian Games was "Thrilling Games, Harmonious Asia" (Chinese: 激情盛会, 和谐亚洲; pinyin: *Jīqíng shènghuì, héxié yàzhōu*).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] It was chosen to represent the goal of the Asian Games which is based on Olympic ideals and values.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The Games aimed to create a competitive atmosphere for participating athletes while promoting unity, peace and friendship among Asian people regardless of differences in race, nationality, religious beliefs and language.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Two years before the games, the "Road of Asia" tour was launched at Tianhe Sports Center to promote the games throughout the region.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A ceremony was held on November 12, 2009, at the Guangzhou Gymnasium to mark the one-year milestone before the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Organizers started selling licensed Asian Games products with introduction of first batch in January 2008.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] On May 7, 2009, the Southern Metropolis Daily newspaper signed a contract with the Guangzhou Asian Games Organizing Committee (GAGOC) and became the exclusive online retailer of licensed products.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The official theme song was released on September 30, 2010, and was called "*Reunion*" (Chinese: 重逢; pinyin: *chóng féng*).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] It was composed by Wu Liqun, with lyrics written by Xu Rongkai.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The English version was translated by Chen Ning Yang, a Chinese-American physicist, and his wife, Weng Fan.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The song was performed by Sun Nan and the late Yao Beina.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Sun Nan also performed it again with Mao Amin for a music video.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The song was selected based from a solicitation campaign for Asian Games songs which received more than 1,600 entries.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] 36 of them were released as selected songs for the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A total of 53 competition venues and 17 training venues were used for the Games, with four venues located outside of Guangzhou.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Events took place at 42 pre-existing venues; eleven competition venues and one training venue were constructed for the Games, while the rest were renovated.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Other venues included the Asian Games Town, which consisted of the Games Village with the Athletes, Officials and Media Buildings, the Main Media Center and the International Broadcast Center.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Organizers revealed that the total investment was over ¥15 billion.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] On April 19, 2009, organizers announced that they had chosen Haixinsha Island on the Pearl River as the venues for the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] This was the first time in the history of the Games that the ceremonies were held outside the Games' main venues.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The villages at the Asian Games Town was built on a 329,024-square-meter land space which had 3,598 apartments in 49 buildings.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Guangzhou's public transportation infrastructure was expanded significantly as a part of the preparation for the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport was upgraded, in contracted with Crisplant (formerly FKI Logistex), to support massive volume of passengers.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A new Wuhan–Guangzhou High-Speed Railway was opened on December 26, 2009, to shorten the travel time between two destinations.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In order to ease traffic congestion and air pollution, the government ordered a 40% reduction of vehicles and offered 1,000 buses for use during the Games and Para Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The government also had a free-ride offer for public transportation during the month of Games, but it was cancelled one week prior to the Games due to an overwhelming response from the citizens.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Instead, the government offered ¥150 (US$23.26) cash subsidies to each household with permanent residence for commuting purposes.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The opening ceremony was held on November 12, 2010.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] For the first time in Asian Games history, the ceremony was not held in a traditional stadium setting.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Instead, it was held at Haixinsha Island, using the Pearl River and Canton Tower as focal points.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The ceremony was directed by Chen Weiya, assistant director of the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing, and featured a cast of about 6,000 performers.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The ceremony lasted for three hours, and together with the closing ceremony cost about ¥380 million (US$58.91 million).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Athletes were paraded by boats along the Pearl River.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The ceremony featured a water-themed arts show and the culture of Guangzhou.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The last torchbearer, diver He Chong, lit up the cauldron after igniting traditional Chinese firecrackers, whose flare shot up to the top of the tower where the cauldron was held.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The ceremony received positive reviews; Rogge was quoted as considering the ceremony to be "absolutely fantastic", and felt that it demonstrated the city's "ability to host the Olympics".
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] OCA director general Husain Al-Musallam also praised the ceremony, arguing that it was unique and "just better than the Beijing Summer Olympics [opening ceremony]".
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] 476 events were held across 42 sports (57 disciplines), including the 26 sports to be played at the 2012 Summer Olympics and 16 additional non-Olympic sports.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] This marked an increase from the 424 events in 39 sports held in 2006.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The OCA approved the return of the Modern Pentathlon and the addition of Cricket (Twenty20) to the official program, while events in dancesport (competitive ballroom dancing), dragon boat, dragon dance, weiqi and roller sport were also held.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Bodybuilding was dropped following criticism over the quality of judging in the competition at the 2006 Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] All 45 members of the Olympic Council of Asia that existed as of 2010 participated in the 2010 Asian Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] All National Olympic Committees were ordered to submit their entries before September 30, 2010.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Organizers allowed each NOC to submit additional entries and injury replacements after the deadline.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] After the final registration deadline, some 9,704 athletes, as well as some 4,750 team officials, took part in the Games, an increase of 184 athletes from the previous Asian Games in Doha.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] According to the Games' official website, Kuwaiti athletes participated the Games under the Olympic flag because the Kuwait Olympic Committee was suspended due to political interference in January 2010.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Below is a list of all the participating NOCs; the number of competitors per delegation is indicated in brackets.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 2010 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Each bullet in these boxes is an event final, the number of bullets per box representing the number of finals that were contested on that day.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The left side of the calendar lists each sport with events held during the Games, and at the right how many gold medals were won in that sport.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] There is a key at the top of the calendar.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The closing ceremony began on November 27, 2010, at 20:06 local time in front of 35,000 spectators.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The Ceremony included the handover of the Games from Guangzhou to Incheon.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The Asian Games flag was symbolically handed over from the city of Guangzhou to the Mayor of Incheon Song Young-gil.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Famous Korean singer, songwriter, dancer, record producer and actor Rain performed.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] China led the medal table for the eighth consecutive time, setting a new record for the most number of gold medals (at 199 gold medals) won in a single Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] This bested their previous record of 183 gold medals won in the 1990 Asian Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Macau and Bangladesh won their first Asian Games gold medals in wushu and cricket, respectively.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Some 35 National Olympic Committees (except Kuwait who competed under the Olympic flag) won at least a single medal.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] 27 NOCs won at least a single gold medal, thus leaving nine NOCs that did not win any medal at the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Guangzhou Asian Games Broadcasting Co., Ltd (GAB) (Chinese: 广州亚运会转播有限公司; pinyin: *Guǎngzhōu yàyùn huì zhuǎnbò yǒuxiàn gōngsī*), a broadcasting consortium established on December 31, 2008, served as the host broadcaster of the games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed within the Asian Games town.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Cricket was among the five debut sports in the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] India, despite its historical record, decided not to send its cricket team to the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] According to the Board of Control for Cricket in India, the decision was due to other international commitments.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] However, its main rivals, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, confirmed their participation.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In ten-pin bowling, the Asian Bowling Federation decided to hold matches without spectators, this resulted in protests from many delegates.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] On November 17, Yang Shu-chun of Chinese Taipei was abruptly disqualified with 12 seconds left in the first round of the taekwondo competition, while leading her opponent 9–0.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] She was accused of having installed illegal sensors on the heel of her socks.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The event quickly turned into an international incident, with officials, politicians and fans from Chinese Taipei, China and South Korea trading accusations of manipulation and fraud.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] About 1,400 random doping tests were carried out during the Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Two athletes tested positive; judoka Shokir Muminov on November 19, 2010, and Greco-Roman wrestler Jakhongir Muminov on November 24, 2010, both from Uzbekistan, tested positive for methylhexanamine.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] On January 24, 2011, the OCA announced another two doping failures, Qatari Ahmed Dheeb who tested positive for exogenous testosterone metabolites and Palestinian Awajna Abdalnasser who tested positive for 19-Norandrosterone.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In July 2010, the citizens of Guangzhou opposed the proposal suggested by the city committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) to use Mandarin more in television news programs, rather than Guangzhou's main language, Cantonese.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The debates eventually led to a series of public protests.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] In late October 2010, in order to protest over the government's language policy in Tibetan areas, the Tibetan Youth Congress (TYC) used the Games as a channel to voice their concerns.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Like the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing, Guangzhou also attempted to improve the city's air quality.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The authority pledged ¥600 million to fight the problem and ordered around 32 chemical plants to stop production by the end of 2009.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] A report from July 13, 2010, indicated that the air quality was rated at 95.07% in 2009, an increase of 12.01% since 2004; this improvement eventually cost authorities ¥24 billion.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Subsequent action from organizers to curb pollution included decreasing the movement of vehicles up to 40% and banning barbecue stalls in 11 cities.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Between 2005 and 2008 about 150 Guolang villagers survived by growing tomatoes, beans, and cabbages while fighting the government for fairer compensation after their homes were flattened for Asian Games infrastructure.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The Panyu government set aside a date to listen to petitioners' complaint on October 18, 2010.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] Prior to the opening of the games, Conghua reported 429 cases of norovirus outbreak.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2010-asian-games] The government officials stressed that the people affected recovered before November 12.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] The **2011 ACC Twenty20 Cup** was played between 3–11 December 2011 in Nepal.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] The tournament acted as a qualifying tournament for the 2012 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] The tournament was won by defending champions Afghanistan who defeated Hong Kong in the final to win the tournament for a third time.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] Afghanistan had already qualified for the World Twenty20 Qualifier as an Associate Member of the International Cricket Council with One Day International status.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] They will be joined in the qualifying event by Hong Kong, Oman and Nepal.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] The top five highest run scorers (total runs) are included in this table.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2011-acc-twenty20-cup] The following table contains the five leading wicket-takers.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The **2012 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier** was played in early 2012 as a part of the ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier series.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] This edition of the qualifier for the 2012 ICC World Twenty20 was an expanded version comprising ten qualifiers from regional Twenty20 tournaments, in addition to the six ODI/Twenty20 status countries.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] ICC Associate and Affiliate Members from around the globe had the opportunity to qualify for the 2012 ICC World Twenty20 in Sri Lanka.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Regional qualifying events were held in the five regions to provide a qualifying pathway to the 16-team qualifier which took place in early 2012 in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The six Associate/Affiliate Members with ODI status – Afghanistan, Canada, Ireland, Kenya, Netherlands and Scotland – have automatically qualified for this event.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Three teams from the Asia region, two teams from Africa, Americas and Europe, and one team from East Asia-Pacific had the opportunity to qualify for the ICC World Twenty20 2012 global qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Some ODI status Associate/Affiliate sides took part in these qualifying events, along with emerging teams from ICC Full Members (e.g., South Africa and Zimbabwe).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] In such cases, the highest placed Associate and Affiliate sides from these events progressed to the global qualifier, based on the qualifying spots available.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The tournament was won by Ireland, who defeated Afghanistan in the final, in a rematch of the 2010 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Both the teams qualified for the 2012 ICC World Twenty20 in Sri Lanka.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Paul Stirling was the highest run-getter with 357 runs including the second-fastest half-century ever in T20I match (17 balls) in the final, while Dawlat Zadran with 17 wickets was the highest wicket-taker.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Namibia's Raymond van Schoor was the Player of the Tournament.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Qualification for 2012 World Twenty20 Qualifier involves 81 ICC member countries to battle their way from regional Division 3 to Division 1 and eventually World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Three of the 81 teams are already qualified but are participating as a part of division members.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Pre-qualified teams are Afghanistan, Canada, and Kenya.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Zimbabwe A team is involved as a part of Africa Division 1 but as a full member Zimbabwe national cricket team is already qualified for 2012 ICC World Twenty20.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] † Switzerland were due to take part, but withdrew due to internal difficulties, and were automatically relegated.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The ten qualified teams from regional Twenty20 competitions played in the 2012 World Twenty20 Qualifier along with the six associate teams that had automatically qualified.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The International Cricket Council announced the umpires to officiate in the tournament.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] There were four Regional Match Referees, plus 12 umpires, seven from the Elite Panel (which included Simon Taufel, a five-time ICC Umpire of the Year Award recipient), and also five ICC Associate and Affiliate Panel umpires.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The tournament, held from 13 to 24 March, has 72 qualifying fixtures.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The sixteen teams participating in this tournament has been divided into two groups of eight each.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The top team from each group will meet in the first qualifying final with the winner being guaranteed a place in the World Twenty20 Cup 2012 to be held in Sri Lanka.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The loser of that match will play the second qualifying final against the winner of a series of playoff matches.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The winners of both qualifying finals will meet in the final at Dubai.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p02] The groups were announced by the ICC on 21 December 2011.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2012-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p02] The top five most runs scorers are included in this table.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-acc-twenty20-cup] The **2013 ACC Twenty20 Cup** was a cricket tournament held between March 26 and April 3 in Nepal.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-acc-twenty20-cup] The tournament served as a qualifying tournament for the 2013 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-acc-twenty20-cup] Afghanistan has already qualified as an ODI nation while UAE has already qualified as host for the 2013 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-acc-twenty20-cup] Hence, the tournament will, in reality, serve as qualifier for other top two teams from Asian region.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The **2013 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier** was played in November 2013 in the United Arab Emirates and is a part of the ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier series.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] This edition of the qualifier for the 2014 ICC World Twenty20 was an expanded version comprising ten qualifiers from regional Twenty20 tournaments in addition to the top six finishers of the previous edition.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The groups were announced by the ICC on 7 August 2013.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Ireland met Afghanistan in the final for the third time with Ireland winning their 2nd title against Afghanistan and 3rd title overall.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The top 6 nations (previously 2) qualified for the 2014 ICC World Twenty20: Ireland, Afghanistan, Netherlands and making their World Twenty20 debut the UAE, Nepal and Hong Kong.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The tournament runs for 16 days with 72 fixtures amongst 16 teams, divided into two groups of eight.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Each group plays a round-robin tournament.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The bottom three teams of each group are immediately eliminated from contention for the top six positions but will play matches to determine which teams finish in positions 11 to 16.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The top three teams from each group compete in the first place playoffs to determine the teams finishing in the top four positions.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The other two teams are relegated to the fifth place playoffs where they compete with the fourth- and fifth-ranked teams from each group for the positions of five to ten.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Both the first and fifth place playoffs are played in a six-team, single-elimination format.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The bottom four teams play in the quarter-finals.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The winners of the quarter-finals compete with the top two teams in the semi-finals.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Playoffs follow to determine the finishing positions of the teams.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] The top six teams qualify for the 2014 ICC World Twenty20.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] They will join the hosts Bangladesh and Zimbabwe in the preliminary group stage, from which only two teams will advance.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p01] Officiating the tournament were three regional match referees and 17 umpires, one of whom was from the Elite Panel and three were on the ICC Associate and Affiliate Panel of Umpires.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p02] † Teams qualified for the 2014 ICC World Twenty20 upon reaching this stage.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/2013-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-p02] Qualified for the 2014 ICC World Twenty20 and 2015 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The **ACC Twenty20 Cup** was a 20-over cricket tournament organised by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The tournament did not include the ACC members who were full members of the International Cricket Council (ICC) during the years in which it was held (Bangladesh, India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka), instead featuring the best associate and affiliate members.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] Matches at the tournament were not accorded official Twenty20 or Twenty20 International status.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The inaugural ACC Twenty20 Cup in 2007 was jointly won by Afghanistan and Oman.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] From 2011, the tournament has been part of the qualification process for the ICC World Twenty20.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The four top-ranked teams at the 2011 and 2013 tournaments qualified for the next World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] At the 2013 Qualifier (for the 2014 main tournament), the four ACC teams all gained Twenty20 International status and automatic qualification for the 2015 Qualifier (for the 2016 main tournament).
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] Consequently, those teams were excluded from the 2015 ACC Twenty20 Cup, with only the winner (Oman) qualifying for the 2016 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The 2007 tournament took place from 27 October until 2 November in Kuwait.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] Ten teams participated in the tournament.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The final between Afghanistan and Oman was tied after 20 overs each.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] Tournament regulations stated that a Bowl-out was to be used in the event of a tie, but due to the poor condition of the pitch after the match, it was cancelled and the trophy shared.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] A second tournament was held in November 2009, featuring all but the bottom two teams from the 2007 tournament.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The cricket team from Afghanistan was the winner again.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The top three teams from the 2009 tournament joined Bangladesh, Pakistan and Sri Lanka for the cricket tournament at the 2010 Asian Games.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] A third tournament was held in December 2011, featuring ten teams.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The cricket team from Afghanistan was the winner for the third time.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The top three teams from the 2011 tournament will head to the UAE to participate in the 2012 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] A fourth tournament was held between March 26- April 3 in Nepal, featuring ten teams.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The cricket team from Afghanistan was the winner for the fourth time.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] Nepal, Hong Kong qualified for the 2013 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier in addition to Afghanistan as an ODI nation and UAE as hosts.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The 2015 edition of the tournament was held in the United Arab Emirates in early 2015.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] The tournament, won by Oman, served as a qualifying tournament for the 2015 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier, to be held in Ireland and Scotland.
[src:acc-twenty20-cup/acc-twenty20-cup] Afghanistan, Hong Kong, Nepal and the United Arab Emirates did not play in the tournament as their T20I status had already placed them in the 2015 World Twenty20 Qualifier.
